title: Grateful Dead Live at Field House, Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute on 1978-05-07
description:
Set 1

Jack Straw, Dire Wolf, Finiculi Finicula, Mexicali Blues-> Mama Tried, Tennessee Jed, It's All Over Now, Friend Of The Devil, Passenger, Brown Eyed Women, The Music Never Stopped

Set 2

Scarlet Begonias-> Fire On The Mountain, Estimated Prophet-> He's Gone-> Drums-> Iko Iko-> The Other One-> Black Peter-> Around & Around, E: U.S. Blues

reviews.review_text: a masterful matrix thank you so much for doing such a bang up job on this beautiful show!!

Fire On Ice how much time did this show at RPI take to master ??  U done good Lou !!  
An they kept on listening. Thanks

Thank You! This show was very important to me for personal reasons. I have been searching for it for quite a while, but one simple mistake kept me coming up empty. Thank you VERY much for putting this here and in such a nice-sounding way. 

While it's a fairly run-of-the-mill show on audio, it was one of the best I've ever been to. The band was relaxed and the audience was happy. There was a real melding of performer and audience, despite the intense heat that couldn't be relieved.

Thanks again!

Thanks for the Great Job Remastering This is one of those shows where it's a miracle that a tape exists at all. 

It was at least 95 degrees inside, open floor (no seats), and utter delirious mayhem at all time. 

The idea that ANYONE could run some sort of recording device is beyond me. (No wonder there were so many tech problems that needed sorting out!) 

Yeah, there may be shows that were better played, but this was one of those nights when the band was happy and the audience was politely nuts. (Clear memories of Bobby, Donna, and Jerry dancing the hula during Iko Iko -- honest!) . 

Thanks for all of your hard work.
smoking music never stopped i was at this show, i would like to thank you for taking the time to make this fine matrix. the music never stopped is red hot .
drums the wildest drums I ever did hear
- Some great moments of genius, marred by some awful trainwrecks.
